The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 IBM plans to lay out a $6-bn spread 

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 President A.P.J. Abdul Kalam with IBM chairman and CEO Samuel J Palmisano in Bangalore on Tuesday. (PTI)

 Bangalore, June 6: IBM is set to log into India gigabyte style with chairman and CEO Samuel J. Palmisano announcing today that the company plans to triple investments to $6 billion (Rs 27,000 crore) in the next three years.

 In the next three years, we will triple our investments in India ? from $2 billion over the last three years to nearly $6 billion, Palmisano said.

 The funds will be utilised for setting up service delivery centres and a telecommunications research centre to cater to the companys telecom clients.

 That investment will ensure that we make the most of the opportunities to grow in this market, while it also enables IBM to fulfil its vision to become a globally integrated company, Palmisano told the companys 10,000 employees here. 

 He said IBM would increase its headcount in India. The company has 43,000 employees in 14 cities.

 Palmisano, on a two-day visit to the country, said India and other emerging economies are critical to IBMs global operations.

 If you are not here in India, making the right investments and finding and developing the best employees and business partners, you wont be able to combine the skills and expertise here with skills and expertise from around the world, in ways that can help our clients be successful, he added. 

 Im here today to say IBM is not going to miss this opportunity. 

 At the meeting, President APJ Abdul Kalam threw a challenge at IBM employees. Can IBM, Indian enterprises and academic institutions with their combined core competence, launch a system or a product that will be new to the world? Nano computers is the answer, he said.




